<span class="header1">NATURE/ANIMALS</span>
<p>If you choose an occupation in this field, you will work  directly with nature and animals. People in these occupations often work as practical scientists. They discover new information about nature because they work closely in it.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Agricultural Scientist</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AF/43207.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Agricultural Scientist" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>An agricultural scientist finds ways to make farming easier and more productive.  As an agricultural scientist, you could work to increase plant production and keep farm animals healthier. You could also work to develop safer pesticides and find better ways to protect water and soil.  For this work, you need a strong background in biology and other sciences.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need at least a Bachelor's Degree to assist an agricultural scientist.  You need a Master's Degree or a Ph.D. to be an agricultural scientist.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>A yearly salary from $35,000 to $65,000 can be expected.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Wildlife Manager</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AF/1270.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Wildlife Manager" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>As a wildlife manager, you would look for ways to protect animals and their habitats.  This means you would not only look after the animals, but also care for their homes. You would make sure the plants, water, and soil of the area were in good shape for the animals. If a problem arises with the habitat, you would be responsible for solving it.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Competition for these jobs is intense.  You need at least a Master's Degree.  The more education and experience you have in caring for wild animals and their habitats, the more likely you are to get a job.  Your leisure activities and part-time jobs can help you to gain experience.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary runs from $21,000 to $80,000 a year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Animal Caretaker</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>An animal caretaker works with non-farm animals.  If you were an animal caretaker, you would work in a zoo, veterinary hospital, pet store or animal shelter.  You would feed and water the animals.  You would bathe, groom and exercise the animals too.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most employers have on-the-job training programs for employees. No college degree is required. There is a need for more animal caretakers.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary ranges from $10,000 to $25,000.</blockquote>

