<span class="header1">TECHNOLOGY</span>
<p>Your active, hands-on way of working and interest in how things work will make you valuable to employers in this occupational field.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Petroleum Engineer</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AF/1323.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Petroleum Engineer" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Petroleum and natural gas are found under the ground.  If you were a petroleum engineer, you would find and retrieve this petroleum and natural gas. You would need to know about rocks and minerals and retrieval methods.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need at least a Bachelor's Degree to become a petroleum engineer. Most engineers get their first jobs with a master's degree.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary ranges from $49,000 to $127,000.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Equipment Operator</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/AF/1396.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Equipment Operator" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Equipment operators use heavy machinery such as cranes, bulldozers, and winches to move dirt, wood, or other materials used in construction.  If you were an equipment operator, you might work at road paving sites.  You might also work at industrial and construction sites.  This equipment can be dangerous.  Safety practices are a big concern.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need a high school diploma for this job.  You are more likely to get a job running expensive equipment if you have taken courses at a vocational school.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>A general salary range for this job is $18,000 to $26,000 per year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Survival Equipment Specialist of the Armed Forces (Military)</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A survival equipment specialist makes sure that equipment such as parachutes, rafts, fire extinguishers, and oxygen tanks are working well.  In this job, you would inspect safety equipment before training sessions or military missions. Others' lives would depend on your work.  You would need to be very thorough and detailed in performing your duties.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You do not need college courses to be a survival equipment specialist.  Shop mechanics and the sciences are high school courses that will help you to get this job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary you receive in the military is based on your rank, years of service, and job.</blockquote>

